The paper presents a framework for motion planning and control of multiple heterogeneous agents, which is a common problem in robotics. The use of motion primitives and a maneuver automaton suggests a focus on control and planning, which is typically covered in the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The use of a non-deterministic algorithm for control policy generation suggests a focus on decision-making and optimization, which is covered in the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The use of feedback-based control and the overall focus on control design suggests a focus on artificial intelligence and machine learning, which is covered in the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of a shortest path algorithm for control policy generation suggests a focus on multi-agent systems, which is covered in the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. Finally, the use of experimental demonstrations suggests a focus on empirical evaluation, which is covered in the Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
